body:
@yaminipreethi, you need compose inputs for each batch. The shape of input_ids and attention_mask is (batch_size, sequence_length). Your example has batch_size=1. Here is an example of batch_size==2:
```
{
     'input_ids': array([
     [    0, 510, 35, 21071, ....., 1, 1],
     [    4, 31, 3, 8, ....., 15, 14],
     ]),
     'attention_mask': array([
        [1, 1, 1, 1, ......, 0, 0],
        [1, 1, 1, 1, ......, 1, 1]])
}
```
If different samples have different sequence lengths,  you will need have some padding logic.

Here is an example code for batching applies to [mlperf](https://github.com/mlcommons/inference/blob/master/language/bert/onnxruntime_SUT.py):
```
        def issue_queries(self, query_samples):
            num_samples = len(query_samples)
            actual_lengths = []
            for i in range(num_samples):
                eval_features = self.qsl.get_features(query_samples[i].index)
                actual_seq_length = sum(eval_features.input_mask)
                actual_lengths.append(actual_seq_length)
            lengths = np.array(actual_lengths)
            sort_index = np.argsort(lengths)

            total_batches = int((num_samples + self.batch_size - 1) / self.batch_size)
            for j in range(total_batches):
                indices = sort_index[self.batch_size * j:self.batch_size * (j + 1)]
                samples = [self.qsl.get_features(query_samples[i].index) for i in indices]
                sample_ids = [query_samples[i].id for i in indices]
                take_lengths = np.take(lengths, indices)
                max_lengths = np.max(take_lengths)

                input_ids = np.zeros((len(samples), max_lengths), dtype=self.input_dtype)
                input_mask = np.zeros((len(samples), max_lengths), dtype=self.input_dtype)
                segment_ids = np.zeros((len(samples), max_lengths), dtype=self.input_dtype)
                for k, sample in enumerate(samples):
                    length = take_lengths[k]
                    input_ids[k, :length] = sample.input_ids[:length]
                    input_mask[k, :length] = sample.input_mask[:length]
                    segment_ids[k, :length] = sample.segment_ids[:length]

                input = {"input_ids": input_ids, self.input_mask_name: input_mask, self.segment_ids_name: segment_ids}

                scores = self.sess.run(self.output_names, input)
```

issue.title: Padding effect quantizied ONNX quality

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body: **Describe the issue** Iâ€™ve quantified ONNX model using quantize_dynamic function. The accuracies of the ONNX model before quantiziation are the same as in the original Pytorch model (also with different padding), but the accuracies are different when I tested the quantified ONNX model on the same sentences but with different padding. My question: How padding effect quantizied ONNX quality? **System information** - OS Platform and Distribution: macOS Big Sur Version 11.4 - ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source - ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.1 - Python version: 3.7 - CPU model and memory: 2.3 GHz 8-Core Intel Core i9 - Memory: 32 GB 2667 MHz DDR4 **To Reproduce** 1. load quantified ONNX model 2. for each sentence padding sentence to specific max length and send it to the model **Expected behavior** Results: I expected that quality (macro F) of quantified ONNX model will be the same for different padding max length like in Pytorch model and ONNX model. Thanks in advanced, Moran

body: @yaminipreethi does batch inference on quantized model give consistent results? for me prediction changes slightly as batch size changes
@rohanshingade, For dynamic quantization, result changes with input. You can try static quantization to see whether you can get consistent results.

> @yaminipreethi does batch inference on quantized model give consistent results? for me prediction changes slightly as batch size changes

Yes, there would be slight difference in results with batch inferencing using quantized model.
